            <abstract>
                <p>This Miracle of Mary in Bartos is attributed to <persName ref="PRS3261Cyrilof">Cyril of Jerusalem</persName>. 
                    It is closely related to <ref type="work" corresp="LIT1201Bartos">Prayer of Mary in Bārtos</ref>, but narrates a different 
                    story of how Mary saved the apostle <persName ref="PRS6902Matthew">Matthew (Mātyās)</persName> who was 
                    imprisoned in the city of ‘Bārtos’ (which is probably derived from ‘Parthia’). When she arrives there, she recites the 
                    <ref type="work" corresp="LIT1201Bartos">prayer of Mary in Bārtos</ref>, which melts all iron, including that of Matthew’s 
                    prison cell, and he is released. This magic prayer was taught to her by Jesus. The text was translated on request by 
                    <persName ref="PRS3429DawitII"><roleName type="office">Emperor</roleName> Dāwit II</persName> from Arabic 
                    in the year <date when="1400">1400 A.D.</date> A related, but very short Miracle, is found in 
                    <ref type="work" corresp="LIT5550MiracleBartos"/>.</p>
            </abstract>
